<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson5_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Quantum State Representation: Bra-Ket</title>


  <section
    xml:id="bra_ket_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Bra-Ket Quantum Representation</title>

    <p> The purpose of <term>Bra-Ket notation</term> is to express the probability of each potential
      outcome. Therefore, there are two parts: The probability and the outcome.</p>

    <p> Bra-ket notation favors ease of calculation over easy readability of the probability,
      but it is easier to read than its alternative, vector notation.</p>

    <p> Each outcome is expressed in a <term>ket</term>, which you've already seen in this textbook: <m>\ket{0}</m>
      , <m>\ket{+}</m>, etc. </p>

    <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
      <p> In the figure to the right, we are expressing the probabilities of measuring apples or
        bananas. Each term in the expression represents a single outcome and are <em>added
          together</em>. The outcome (apple or banana) is placed inside of the ket, and the <term>probability
        amplitude</term> (rather than the probability) is placed just before the ket. </p>

      <image source="L5.3.braket.png" width="66%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p> The relationship between probability amplitude and probability is:</p>

    <p>
      <md>\text{probability} = |\text{probability amplitude}|^2</md>
    </p>

    <p> In this notation, if there is equal probability, or 1/2 probability of each of two
      outcomes,
      then it will be: </p>

    <p>
      <insert>picture like the one above with apples and bananas but with the terms 1/rt(2)
        for each</insert>
    </p>

    <p> Put in a question here using heads or tails coins in bra-ket notation and ask what the
      probability is of each outcome.</p>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket Heads and Tails">
      <title>Coin Flip in Bra-Ket Notation</title>
      <idx>bra-ket coin flip</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>H</m> is heads and <m>T</m> is tails, what is the probability of getting heads and
          tails for the following state?</p>
        <p>
          <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{H} + \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{T}</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{3}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! By squaring each probability amplitude, you get the probability of
              getting the corresponding outcome.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Remember that the bra-ket notation shows probability amplitudes, not probability.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{2}{3}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you associate the probability with the corresponding outcome.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{2}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>This is a special coin! Make sure you check probabilities from the bra-ket notation.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Bra-ket notation uses probability amplitudes, which are squared to get probabilities.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>


    <p> We can see that this notation is very flexible to represent all kinds of probabilities. If
      we want to express outcomes from the raincoat/raining example from (<xref
        ref="sec-independent-probabilities" />), it would look like the following:</p>

    <p>50% chance of sun, 50% chance of rain:</p>
    <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{☀️} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
      \ket{🌧️}</md>

    <p>75% chance of no raincoat, 25% chance of raincoat:</p>
    <md>\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}} \ket{👕} + \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}} \ket{🧥}
      = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{👕} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{🧥}</md>

    <p>Remember: to compute probability amplitudes for bra-ket notation, calculate the <em>square
      root</em> of the probability of each outcome.</p>

    <p> In quantum computing, the possible values for a quantum bit (qubit) are 0 or 1. So
      a qubit in a 50/50 superposition of 0 and 1 would have the state: </p>

    <md>\ket{+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </md>

    <p> If there is negative phase, then it will be placed on the 1 state: </p>
    <md>\ket{-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </md>

    <p> A few exercises - give a state and answer the probabilities,
      give the probabilities and answer the state. Through in phase into one of them.</p>

  </section>

  <section
    xml:id="multi-qubit-bra_ket" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multi-qubit Bra-ket Notation</title>

    <p> We can also combine two independent qubits into a 2-qubit bra-ket notation, just like we
      represented two qubits using our visual representation (<xref ref="sec-two-qubit-visual" />).
      An individual qubit only has two possible outcomes: 0 or 1. For a pair of qubits, we have each
      combination of possible outcomes: 00, 01, 10, 11. The tricky part is how to calculate the
      probability of those combined events from the single qubit probabilities. This is when our
      independent probability calculations come into play <mdash /> you just multiply the
      appropriate values together. </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.1to2qubitsbraket.png" width="60%" />
    </p>

    <p>This might look familiar: combining independent qubits is analogous to distribution when
      multiplying two additive terms in algebra!</p>

    <md>
      <mrow>(a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}) (c\ket{0} + d\ket{1}) \amp= ac\ket{00} + ad\ket{01} + bc\ket{10} +
        bd\ket{11}</mrow>
      <mrow>(ax + by) (cx + dy) \amp= ac(x^2) + ad(xy) + bc(yx) + bd(y^2)</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>The same rules apply when combining more than two independent qubits.</p>

    <insert>TODO: show factoring example, referencing entanglement in the future</insert>

    <insert> Put in some questions here with 2 qubits and 3 qubits - can grab from my homeworks.</insert>

  </section>


  <section
    xml:id="bra_ket_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Bra-Ket State Simplification</title>

    <p>Just like with fractions, there are multiple ways of expressing the same state. Every time a
      state is calculated, we then simplify the state into its preferred form. We saw some similar
      simplification rules for our visual representation in <xref
        ref="sec-simplify-superposition-visual" />. Let's learn a few simplification rules for
      bra-ket notation!</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>The order of the outcomes is always in increasing numeric order
          (starting with all 0's and ending with all 1's). Below is a properly formed
          3-qubit state: </p>
        <md>a\ket{000} + b\ket{001} + c\ket{010} + d\ket{011} + e\ket{100} + f\ket{101} + g\ket{110}
          + h\ket{111}</md>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>You may omit any term whose probability is 0. </p>
        <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + 0\ket{01} + 0\ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}</md>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>The first term in the state (the <term>leading term</term>) is never in negative phase.
          As we discussed previously ( <xref ref="sec-global-phase" />), global phase has no
          physical meaning; so if the leading term is negative, you can multiply the whole state by <m>-1</m>
          .</p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <note>
      <p> One rule that is different from algebraic expressions is that you can multiply all terms
        by the same number and the resulting state is the same; the <em>comparison</em> of the
        states is what matters, not the absolute values. However, the purpose of bra-ket notation is
        to be easily able to tell by looking at it what the probabilities of each outcome are (and
        still be able to perform operations). Therefore, we prefer to keep bra-ket states <term>
        normalized</term> .</p>

      <p> To normalize a bra-ket state, we want to ensure that the coefficients of each term
        represent probability amplitudes. In order to do so, the sum of the squares of each
        coefficient should add up to 1. This represents the fact that there is a 100% chance of
        getting any of the outcomes expressed in the state. For example, for a single qubit of the
        form <m>a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}</m>, <m>a^2 + b^2 = 1</m>.</p>
    </note>

    <note>
      <p>If all outcomes are the same probability some people omit the leading term.
        However, none of the answers in this book use this rule because it hides the true
        probability.</p>
    </note>
  </section>
</section>
